involved narrative document to solve this problem that the team had been having with the story,

90
00:05:18,862 --> 00:05:25,609
and especially the later parts of the story. And so we submitted this document, and we were

91
00:05:25,649 --> 00:05:29,512
expecting some kind of creative feedback, because finally it got up to the creative director.

92
00:05:30,388 --> 00:05:33,289
And after everything, after working on this super hard,

93
00:05:33,309 --> 00:05:35,950
after trying to navigate it and trying to give something of ourselves

94
00:05:35,990 --> 00:05:37,011
to the team that they had asked for,

95
00:05:37,891 --> 00:05:40,772
we got this quote that we'll never forget from the creative director

96
00:05:41,072 --> 00:05:42,513
who had nothing to say about the narrative,

97
00:05:42,533 --> 00:05:43,933
nothing to say about any of the creative.

98
00:05:44,633 --> 00:05:47,495
It was just an email that says,

99
00:05:47,595 --> 00:05:50,336
Why are outsourcers writing our ending?

100
00:05:51,276 --> 00:05:52,216
Because that was all that mattered.

101
00:05:52,397 --> 00:05:53,957
It didn't matter what we did, it mattered who we were.

102
00:05:54,357 --> 00:05:56,958
And so we left the project at that point within days.

103
00:05:58,713 --> 00:06:03,118
So finally Project C is a little different in that this is a project we worked on on

