00:07:54,970 --> 00:07:57,030
We're relatively new to the game.

151
00:07:57,550 --> 00:07:59,771
But this talk, I just want to make sure

152
00:07:59,831 --> 00:08:00,632
is not just for venting.

153
00:08:00,832 --> 00:08:02,832
It's mostly to share some realizations that we've had.

154
00:08:03,232 --> 00:08:06,033
The first, I think, being that our issues with clients

155
00:08:06,674 --> 00:08:09,094
tend to fall into two distinct categories.

156
00:08:09,875 --> 00:08:16,083
The first is a lack of clarity on how our work even functions, how narrative works.

157
00:08:16,103 --> 00:08:18,245
Not in our case, but I think it goes across the board.

158
00:08:18,566 --> 00:08:22,811
Because a lot of times we find that when we're hired, there's a faulty perspective on what

159
00:08:22,871 --> 00:08:25,695
writers and narrative designers need to work and how they work.

160
00:08:26,035 --> 00:08:28,518
There's this assumption that you get a contractor fully formed.

161
00:08:29,419 --> 00:08:33,241
But the second focus is a lack of focus on people

162
00:08:33,841 --> 00:08:38,083
and a perception of projects as being importantly work first, game first,

163
00:08:38,604 --> 00:08:41,545
and then humans second, contractors third.

164
00:08:42,426 --> 00:08:46,248
And I think looking at those, regardless of what we do, like...

165
00:08:46,997 --> 00:08:48,277
if we weren't in narrative or writing,

166
00:08:48,297 --> 00:08:49,858
I think we'd still have this problem as contractors.

167
00:08:50,358 --> 00:08:53,439
We see that it's core, the core issue here is a way

168
00:08:53,540 --> 00:08:57,401
that teams and companies view contractors and outside help.

169
00:08:57,561 --> 00:08:59,662
So the question becomes how are contractors seen?

170
00:09:01,203 --> 00:09:02,403
And I think from our perspective,

171
00:09:02,584 --> 00:09:04,124
a fundamental issue is that contractors

172
00:09:04,244 --> 00:09:05,885
are often perceived as a tool.

173
00:09:06,225 --> 00:09:07,366
They're like a hammer that you can grab

174
00:09:07,386 --> 00:09:09,287
to go at some nails and in a good scenario

175
00:09:09,307 --> 00:09:10,187
just be an easy solve.

176
00:09:11,047 --> 00:09:14,090
And contractors are also seen as workers who can perform a task

177
00:09:14,150 --> 00:09:16,032
without like the pesky overhead of HR.

178
00:09:16,413 --> 00:09:18,495
They're a quick fix, little context is needed,

179
00:09:18,515 --> 00:09:22,199
and contractors provide a way to weaponize talent

180
00:09:22,239 --> 00:09:24,962
without the company having to consider the human behind it.

181
00:09:25,262 --> 00:09:27,284
We become this extension of the team itself,

182
00:09:27,945 --> 00:09:29,407
but wielded by their hand.

183
00:09:30,448 --> 00:09:31,068
And I think...

184
00:09:32,180 --> 00:09:39,002
In a cohesive, empathetic, kind, community-focused, organized, well-produced, and efficient game

185
00:09:39,042 --> 00:09:42,862
production process, this relationship could be a beautiful symbiosis.

186
00:09:43,943 --> 00:09:47,403
But that's just not how most games work.

187
00:09:47,763 --> 00:09:53,084
There are no nails simple enough to just wield a hammer against them, and to me what contractors

188
00:09:53,164 --> 00:09:55,445
are in an ideal scenario here is collaborators.

189
00:09:56,285 --> 00:09:57,765
People you invite into your team.

190
00:09:58,678 --> 00:10:03,041
Because with luck, you've hired people who are experts in their own field and who are deeply knowledgeable of the discipline,

191
00:10:03,481 --> 00:10:07,303
and who have taken that knowledge and made a living not only from that knowledge,

192
00:10:07,483 --> 00:10:12,365
but of grasping context very quickly, producing that very efficiently,

193
00:10:12,706 --> 00:10:14,787
and applying their knowledge to a project in an ongoing manner.

194
00:10:15,607 --> 00:10:21,910
And while it's tempting, I think, to assume that this external role of a contractor or a craftsperson here

195
00:10:23,111 --> 00:10:25,752
creates distance between that person and the team,

196
00:10:26,533 --> 00:10:27,713
I think that the reality that...

197
00:10:28,570 --> 00:10:31,591
is that games require creative collaboration and shared vision.

198
00:10:32,191 --> 00:10:34,492
And there's often actually more work

199
00:10:34,952 --> 00:10:37,553
to be done to bring contractors in to share that vision

200
00:10:37,993 --> 00:10:39,814
and to make them cohesively, and in terms

201
00:10:39,834 --> 00:10:43,495
of their own perspective and knowledge, part of that system.

202
00:10:44,355 --> 00:10:47,756
So to that end, we came up with some guidelines, just

203
00:10:47,776 --> 00:10:50,377
some thoughts and stuff that David's going to take us

204
00:10:50,417 --> 00:10:51,997
through, and that hopefully provide

205
00:10:52,017 --> 00:10:54,598
at least the beginnings of some structure or just some ideas

206
00:10:54,638 --> 00:10:57,659
to think on about how we can do this better.

207
00:11:00,050 --> 00:11:04,033
All right, hi, I'm David.

208
00:11:04,233 --> 00:11:05,153
We've said it before already,

209
00:11:05,193 --> 00:11:07,095
but every collaboration is challenging to some degree.

210
00:11:07,135 --> 00:11:09,096
That's just what collaborations are.

211
00:11:09,917 --> 00:11:11,378
But we've found solutions to lean on

212
00:11:11,418 --> 00:11:13,239
when challenges do happen, because they will.

213
00:11:13,860 --> 00:11:15,461
We've worked through the challenges,

214
00:11:15,561 --> 00:11:17,422
and we now know things that we wished we knew

215
00:11:17,482 --> 00:11:19,124
before we left some of these projects.

216
00:11:19,284 --> 00:11:20,124
So, first up.

217
00:11:21,107 --> 00:11:23,147
We're going to talk about what to do before you're

218
00:11:23,167 --> 00:11:24,407
bringing in external collaborators.

219
00:11:24,748 --> 00:11:26,248
The very first question you need to ask yourself

220
00:11:27,008 --> 00:11:29,909
is, why do you want to bring on an external collaborator?

221
00:11:30,309 --> 00:11:32,070
What is the problem that you're trying to fix?

222
00:11:32,930 --> 00:11:34,430
And really, the real question is,

223
00:11:34,570 --> 00:11:36,051
are you ready to solve this problem?

224
00:11:36,731 --> 00:11:39,212
Or do you wish to be told that there is no problem?

225
00:11:40,072 --> 00:11:41,172
If you're bringing in a producer,

226
00:11:41,852 --> 00:11:43,453
are you ready to change the way you're doing things?

227
00:11:43,813 --> 00:11:45,173
If you're bringing in a sound designer,

228
00:11:45,773 --> 00:11:47,214
are you ready to invest in some tools

229
00:11:47,414 --> 00:11:49,695
so that they are able to do their work better?

230
00:11:50,732 --> 00:11:52,292
if you're bringing in a sensitivity reader.

231
00:11:52,972 --> 00:11:54,573
Are you ready to examine your own biases

232
00:11:54,653 --> 00:11:55,893
because it's going to happen?

233
00:11:56,853 --> 00:11:58,894
We can sense as collaborators

234
00:11:59,374 --> 00:12:02,775
when the client is asking for safety

235
00:12:02,995 --> 00:12:04,095
versus asking for changes.

236
00:12:04,656 --> 00:12:06,616
And the best collaborations are when people

237
00:12:06,896 --> 00:12:08,097
are willing to change.

238
00:12:10,267 --> 00:12:11,547
Next question is, what are you paying for?

239
00:12:11,907 --> 00:12:14,488
Are you paying for an opinion that you are maybe or maybe

240
00:12:14,508 --> 00:12:15,348
not going to implement?

241
00:12:16,008 --> 00:12:18,169
Are you paying for a content producer with strict

242
00:12:18,209 --> 00:12:21,249
deadlines, or are you paying for a co-creator with many

243
00:12:21,309 --> 00:12:23,430
responsibilities and lots of autonomy?

244
00:12:24,230 --> 00:12:25,671
These are all very, very different.

245
00:12:25,811 --> 00:12:26,831
They're quoted differently.

246
00:12:26,871 --> 00:12:27,731
The contract is different.

247
00:12:27,751 --> 00:12:28,831
They're built differently.

248
00:12:29,732 --> 00:12:32,794
and they need different levels of access and onboarding to your project.

249
00:12:32,854 --> 00:12:36,056
You have to be ready for this and you have to adapt based on what you actually want.

250
00:12:36,736 --> 00:12:39,938
And the other question you need to ask yourself, because we always get asked this, is

251
00:12:41,039 --> 00:12:43,540
is it really full-time or are you just trying to lock them down?

252
00:12:44,481 --> 00:12:47,863
There is no benefit in locking down a freelancer. We're used to doing the work

253
00:12:48,383 --> 00:12:52,886
on time according to your schedule. If they take the work, it's because they know that they can do

254
00:12:52,926 --> 00:12:59,050
this in this amount of time. No need for full-time if the freelancer knows that they can do this work.

255
00:13:00,391 --> 00:13:04,534
Remember, freelancers get better because they do more projects at the same time.

256
00:13:04,914 --> 00:13:08,456
They accumulate more experience over a shorter amount of time because they touch many different

257
00:13:08,496 --> 00:13:08,896
projects.

258
00:13:09,457 --> 00:13:10,677
And locking them down prevents that.

259
00:13:13,339 --> 00:13:15,741
Before you sign the contract, you're going to want to talk about deliverables.

260
00:13:16,621 --> 00:13:20,203
The first question is, do you know deliverables ahead of time as the client?

261
00:13:20,363 --> 00:13:21,684
You might not, and that's okay.

262
00:13:21,704 --> 00:13:25,026
But that means you're not asking for a content producer, you're asking for somebody to fill

263
00:13:25,066 --> 00:13:26,367
a full role within your team.

264
00:13:27,419 --> 00:13:29,561
And then when that happens, you have to ask yourself,

265
00:13:29,681 --> 00:13:31,302
who's going to determine the deliverables?

266
00:13:31,942 --> 00:13:35,925
More often than you think, we, as contractors,

267
00:13:36,366 --> 00:13:37,947
are asked to onboard to a project,

268
00:13:38,067 --> 00:13:40,149
and then we're asked, okay, what should we do first?

269
00:13:40,829 --> 00:13:42,750
So we have to determine the steps

270
00:13:42,791 --> 00:13:44,752
between nothing and something.

271
00:13:45,733 --> 00:13:47,594
When that happens, we become a team member,

272
00:13:47,854 --> 00:13:48,915
whether we're contractors or not.

273
00:13:49,495 --> 00:13:51,677
And we're hired for our expertise, not just our time.

274
00:13:52,418 --> 00:13:52,678
And so...

275
00:13:53,743 --> 00:13:58,407
you as a client end up bringing someone who will need to be very embedded in the team.

276
00:13:58,887 --> 00:14:03,111
It's important to have that conversation before the contract to determine the place that your

277
00:14:03,151 --> 00:14:08,516
contractor is going to have within your team ahead of time and to make that space in your team

278
00:14:09,096 --> 00:14:15,842
within your project. We're always asked in the first opening calls when's the right moment to

279
00:14:15,862 --> 00:14:16,903
bring us on and

280
00:14:18,276 --> 00:14:19,517
We don't really know what the right time is.

281
00:14:19,577 --> 00:14:20,758
It depends for every project.

282
00:14:20,798 --> 00:14:21,719
We do know one thing, though.

283
00:14:22,159 --> 00:14:23,641
There is such a thing as too late.

284
00:14:24,942 --> 00:14:26,943
And when there isn't time to do meaningful work,

285
00:14:26,963 --> 00:14:29,125
when you're up against the wall and you're like,

286
00:14:29,145 --> 00:14:30,947
we're gonna bring in somebody because we're out of time,

287
00:14:31,527 --> 00:14:33,549
chances are this collaborator will also not have

288
00:14:33,589 --> 00:14:34,950
enough time to do their work.

289
00:14:35,370 --> 00:14:37,452
And it might not be a good idea to bring someone else

290
00:14:37,492 --> 00:14:40,054
to the mix who will also get crunched

291
00:14:40,174 --> 00:14:42,596
and turn in subpar work due to the circumstances.

292
00:14:44,379 --> 00:14:47,320
And there is also no such thing as too early.

293
00:14:48,221 --> 00:14:49,702
Oftentimes, clients will wait to be

294
00:14:50,222 --> 00:14:52,383
ready to bring somebody on, to have enough documentation,

295
00:14:52,443 --> 00:14:54,824
to have enough for the vision to stabilize.

296
00:14:54,844 --> 00:14:57,466
And the best way we found to work, honestly,

297
00:14:57,566 --> 00:14:59,747
is as early as possible so that we can follow the project

298
00:14:59,787 --> 00:15:00,027
along.

299
00:15:00,227 --> 00:15:02,229
It's not about influencing the project.

300
00:15:02,289 --> 00:15:04,910
It's about knowing and being there and avoiding pitfalls

301
00:15:05,030 --> 00:15:05,831
before they happen.

302
00:15:06,411 --> 00:15:08,112
So we like to onboard very early on

303
00:15:08,512 --> 00:15:11,134
and do regular check-ins monthly or quarterly

304
00:15:11,214 --> 00:15:12,094
before production starts.

305
00:15:14,010 --> 00:15:15,851
That way we have time to build project knowledge.

306
00:15:16,512 --> 00:15:21,436
We can add our opinions and influences to the project when it's needed, in order to

307
00:15:21,476 --> 00:15:23,657
be ready to hit the ground running when the production starts.

308
00:15:24,698 --> 00:15:29,302
This avoids things like calling into question major game pillars halfway through production

309
00:15:29,342 --> 00:15:30,102
because we weren't there.

310
00:15:31,277 --> 00:15:33,599
before we actually had to encounter them.

311
00:15:34,480 --> 00:15:36,042
This prep time is not time consuming.

312
00:15:36,902 --> 00:15:38,944
This can happen as a couple times a month,

313
00:15:39,104 --> 00:15:40,386
which means it's a couple hours for us

314
00:15:40,486 --> 00:15:41,747
and it's not super expensive.

315
00:15:42,227 --> 00:15:45,110
And it really helps collaboration be easier in the long run.

316
00:15:45,130 --> 00:15:47,772
So please consider bringing any external collaborators

317
00:15:47,792 --> 00:15:49,454
you would want early on,

318
00:15:49,714 --> 00:15:51,356
even just to see what the product is like

319
00:15:51,596 --> 00:15:53,458
and to have a long ramp way

320
00:15:54,619 --> 00:15:56,400
towards your successful collaboration.

321
00:15:58,433 --> 00:15:59,834
Now, you've decided to work with a collaborator,

322
00:15:59,995 --> 00:16:00,975
and you've signed the contract.

323
00:16:01,376 --> 00:16:02,536
We have some guidelines for that, too.

324
00:16:04,618 --> 00:16:06,579
You have to remember that they're game developers.

325
00:16:07,280 --> 00:16:09,421
The way contracting works, oftentimes,

326
00:16:09,641 --> 00:16:12,544
is that we will have one point of contact with your team,

327
00:16:12,564 --> 00:16:13,965
somebody who's responsible for talking to us.

328
00:16:15,125 --> 00:16:16,446
And it's also their responsibility,

329
00:16:16,506 --> 00:16:17,867
because we're game developers, to give us

330
00:16:17,907 --> 00:16:20,089
as much information as possible on the game.

331
00:16:21,310 --> 00:16:23,291
And that's on top of their regular responsibilities

332
00:16:23,832 --> 00:16:24,252
on your team.

333
00:16:25,288 --> 00:16:27,009
This means that despite their best efforts,

334
00:16:27,429 --> 00:16:30,170
they're only human, and we can't get a full vision

335
00:16:30,210 --> 00:16:31,971
of what's happening on your entire team.

336
00:16:32,391 --> 00:16:33,411
And we're kept in the dark.

337
00:16:33,912 --> 00:16:35,152
And we can't do our best work

338
00:16:35,372 --> 00:16:36,913
without the context of your wider game,

339
00:16:37,593 --> 00:16:38,694
just like your regular employees.

340
00:16:39,614 --> 00:16:42,255
So don't treat your contractors like a service house.

341
00:16:43,035 --> 00:16:44,716
External developers do their best work

342
00:16:44,756 --> 00:16:46,017
when they are part of the team.

343
00:16:46,557 --> 00:16:48,778
Invite them to syncs and end of sprint reviews,

344
00:16:49,358 --> 00:16:50,559
and have them meet the whole team,

345
00:16:50,699 --> 00:16:52,439
even if it's just like an hour long of fun facts.

346
00:16:53,942 --> 00:16:58,564
And don't just have a private channel where you talk to the contractors in one person.

347
00:16:58,604 --> 00:16:59,384
That's never useful.

348
00:16:59,644 --> 00:17:02,685
Bring them into the full Slack channel, have them embedded in the team, have them participate

349
00:17:02,705 --> 00:17:03,185
in activities.

350
00:17:03,705 --> 00:17:07,327
More collaboration and more connections, more access means better work at the end of the

351
00:17:07,347 --> 00:17:07,487
day.

352
00:17:10,568 --> 00:17:11,328
The other thing is time.

353
00:17:13,095 --> 00:17:15,095
In case you don't know, freelancers plan their own work

354
00:17:15,155 --> 00:17:15,756
according to time.

355
00:17:15,856 --> 00:17:17,796
They have a week, and they're slotting

356
00:17:17,836 --> 00:17:19,657
all these different projects in that week

357
00:17:19,717 --> 00:17:21,197
to be able to meet their deadlines.

358
00:17:22,398 --> 00:17:23,878
And they need their own calendars for that.

359
00:17:24,578 --> 00:17:26,719
They can't really have waiting periods

360
00:17:26,999 --> 00:17:28,359
to start or complete a deliverable.

361
00:17:28,899 --> 00:17:30,220
A waiting freelancer is a freelancer

362
00:17:30,260 --> 00:17:32,461
whose personal calendar is getting really messed up,

363
00:17:32,841 --> 00:17:35,181
and that leads to worse work at the end of the day.

364
00:17:35,401 --> 00:17:36,922
That's why you're having all these conversations

365
00:17:37,022 --> 00:17:37,682
before you start.

366
00:17:39,440 --> 00:17:41,161
Remember to give feedback in a timely manner.

367
00:17:41,941 --> 00:17:43,902
It sucks to send something and hear nothing back.

368
00:17:43,982 --> 00:17:44,682
It always sucks.

369
00:17:45,203 --> 00:17:47,764
But also, if you hear feedback two weeks on,

370
00:17:48,604 --> 00:17:51,066
you have to reacclimate and context switch back

371
00:17:51,166 --> 00:17:52,706
onto this project every single time.

372
00:17:53,971 --> 00:17:54,671
So keep that in mind.

373
00:17:54,711 --> 00:17:56,292
The same thing applies if we require more time

374
00:17:56,313 --> 00:17:57,053
from your freelancers.

375
00:17:57,754 --> 00:17:59,255
Always remember that if you're crunching,

376
00:17:59,335 --> 00:18:00,616
your collaborators are crunching too,

377
00:18:00,656 --> 00:18:03,938
there's no such thing as one without the other.

378
00:18:04,038 --> 00:18:04,939
You have to acknowledge this.

379
00:18:04,979 --> 00:18:06,380
You can't just like bury your head in the sand

380
00:18:06,420 --> 00:18:07,661
and pretend that everything is fine.

381
00:18:07,861 --> 00:18:09,202
They're freelancers, they're used to it.

382
00:18:09,863 --> 00:18:11,264
You have to have a conversation about this.

383
00:18:12,004 --> 00:18:13,125
And don't take it for granted.

384
00:18:14,266 --> 00:18:16,248
And the last thing is if your deadlines

385
00:18:16,308 --> 00:18:17,709
change midway through production,

386
00:18:17,829 --> 00:18:20,050
it's because your team can't meet

387
00:18:21,046 --> 00:18:24,027
deadline. They can't produce the work in the time you've allotted ahead of time.

388
00:18:25,088 --> 00:18:28,929
So why wouldn't the calendar of the contractor change as well? We know that

389
00:18:28,949 --> 00:18:31,810
there's a date on the contract, we know that there's a deliverable, but if the

390
00:18:31,890 --> 00:18:34,711
whole project changes then that contract doesn't fit with what you're making

391
00:18:34,771 --> 00:18:41,014
anyway. So have the conversation to, you know, open up the contract again, see how

392
00:18:41,054 --> 00:18:43,855
we can collaborate better, and see how we can get to the finish line together

393
00:18:44,175 --> 00:18:44,375
better.

394
00:18:47,528 --> 00:18:48,909
A topic that's very near and dear to my heart,

395
00:18:49,530 --> 00:18:50,810
not Garfield, iteration.

396
00:18:52,652 --> 00:18:53,472
This is video games.

397
00:18:53,572 --> 00:18:55,053
Nothing's ever right on the first try.

398
00:18:55,073 --> 00:18:57,215
I don't think I'm saying anything new here at GDC.

399
00:18:58,195 --> 00:18:59,816
Nothing ever fits on first delivery.

400
00:18:59,836 --> 00:19:02,198
It has to be tested, balanced, edited, reviewed,

401
00:19:02,258 --> 00:19:04,359
whatever the hell it is.

402
00:19:04,399 --> 00:19:05,840
Sorry for swearing, I'm French.

403
00:19:07,201 --> 00:19:08,402
There will be many passes.

404
00:19:08,502 --> 00:19:10,123
This is the normal process.

405
00:19:11,929 --> 00:19:13,810
So don't build your calendars expecting collaborators

406
00:19:14,230 --> 00:19:15,892
who have less visibility on your project

407
00:19:16,172 --> 00:19:17,093
to get it right the first time.

408
00:19:17,533 --> 00:19:19,154
It's not because they're bad at their jobs.

409
00:19:19,334 --> 00:19:21,516
It's because they need iteration just like everybody else

410
00:19:21,576 --> 00:19:22,016
on your team.

411
00:19:22,377 --> 00:19:23,878
This is the process of making games.

412
00:19:25,079 --> 00:19:25,979
And to that effect.

413
00:19:27,085 --> 00:19:31,991
integrate. We need to see our first passes in the game to know if it's good. We need to see it in

414
00:19:32,131 --> 00:19:38,518
action in order to improve it and make it better. This applies to everybody. Your wider team has a

415
00:19:38,818 --> 00:19:42,963
better perspective on the project and everything going on in the game and getting your collaborators

416
00:19:43,043 --> 00:19:48,149
work in the game will allow your team to react to this content and help improve it for future passes.

417
00:19:49,503 --> 00:19:52,426
To make it simple, integrate the content into the game

418
00:19:52,686 --> 00:19:55,588
to compensate for the fact that your collaborators are not

419
00:19:55,749 --> 00:19:58,891
fully integrated into your team.

420
00:19:59,912 --> 00:20:01,874
Honestly, you'd be surprised at how much times we've sent

421
00:20:01,954 --> 00:20:03,796
scripts and we don't see them in-game ever.

422
00:20:03,976 --> 00:20:05,017
And we get lots of notes on them,

423
00:20:05,457 --> 00:20:09,461
but we can't help them make them better until they're in-game.

424
00:20:09,481 --> 00:20:11,383
And we can also add our perspective to this.

425
00:20:14,157 --> 00:20:17,763
We've said this a couple times before, but contractors are honing one specific skill

426
00:20:17,903 --> 00:20:19,506
across multiple different productions at once.

427
00:20:20,893 --> 00:20:23,595
Generally speaking, you are an expert in your game.

428
00:20:23,635 --> 00:20:25,536
You've spent thousands of hours and years

429
00:20:26,356 --> 00:20:27,837
learning and figuring out and knowing

430
00:20:27,897 --> 00:20:28,977
how to make this specific game.

431
00:20:29,058 --> 00:20:31,379
But think of the fact that the freelancers that you're hiring,

432
00:20:32,579 --> 00:20:35,321
the same thing goes for them and their field of expertise

433
00:20:35,761 --> 00:20:36,901
across many different games.

434
00:20:37,422 --> 00:20:39,143
They spend their time being the best

435
00:20:39,223 --> 00:20:41,464
at doing what they do across multiple different productions

436
00:20:41,764 --> 00:20:44,165
on multiple different scales, multiple different scopes.

437
00:20:44,825 --> 00:20:46,906
In our case, from AAA to a very small indie.

438
00:20:47,166 --> 00:20:51,328
So we know how to do narrative on any type of production.

439
00:20:51,368 --> 00:20:53,949
So oftentimes, the problem isn't about your project.

440
00:20:54,049 --> 00:20:58,130
It's about making our expertise fit with the project at hand.

441
00:20:59,191 --> 00:21:00,311
So listen to your collaborators.

442
00:21:00,591 --> 00:21:01,372
They're experts.

443
00:21:01,692 --> 00:21:04,253
And remember, don't hire people to tell you

444
00:21:05,093 --> 00:21:06,854
things that you think you know better than them.

445
00:21:07,074 --> 00:21:09,275
That's not going to lead to successful collaboration.

446
00:21:09,735 --> 00:21:10,695
You hired them for a reason.

447
00:21:11,879 --> 00:21:14,743
Work requires vulnerability, experience, energy,

448
00:21:15,083 --> 00:21:16,445
and thus it requires humanity.

449
00:21:17,366 --> 00:21:19,869
A task can have taken 15 minutes to perform,

450
00:21:20,269 --> 00:21:21,871
but it requires thousands of hours

451
00:21:21,931 --> 00:21:23,593
honing a craft to do in this amount of time.

452
00:21:24,334 --> 00:21:27,418
You're paying to access a human being with life experience

453
00:21:27,778 --> 00:21:29,861
who knows how to do their job, so please respect that.

454
00:21:33,335 --> 00:21:35,535
And finally, here's something everybody knows.

455
00:21:35,895 --> 00:21:37,636
Games change scope during development.

456
00:21:37,776 --> 00:21:38,896
It's just what games do.

457
00:21:40,116 --> 00:21:41,376
And that's why we like doing this.

458
00:21:42,756 --> 00:21:44,717
Sometimes that happens while your contractors

459
00:21:44,737 --> 00:21:45,597
are working on the project.

460
00:21:46,157 --> 00:21:48,398
The thing you have to remember is, yes, we

461
00:21:48,458 --> 00:21:49,978
will sense it as it's happening.

462
00:21:50,078 --> 00:21:51,658
We'll see that what we're trying to do

463
00:21:51,778 --> 00:21:53,959
doesn't quite fit with what you're doing.

464
00:21:55,259 --> 00:21:57,079
But they should also be told about it.

465
00:21:57,119 --> 00:21:58,659
You can't just assume that they'll find out

466
00:21:58,679 --> 00:21:59,340
from somebody else.

467
00:21:59,800 --> 00:22:01,600
There needs to be a conversation about the game's scope

468
00:22:01,620 --> 00:22:02,200
and how it's changing.

469
00:22:03,798 --> 00:22:06,199
Because change in scope means change in expectations.

470
00:22:06,659 --> 00:22:08,740
Employees can weather a change in scope

471
00:22:08,760 --> 00:22:09,921
because they can wait around for a little bit.

472
00:22:09,941 --> 00:22:12,302
You're paying them full time to weather this change.

473
00:22:12,722 --> 00:22:14,863
But contractors are deliverable based

474
00:22:14,883 --> 00:22:16,024
and they have other things going on.

475
00:22:16,464 --> 00:22:18,786
They need to have the relationship re-evaluated

476
00:22:18,826 --> 00:22:20,567
and re-examined when these changes occur.

477
00:22:20,927 --> 00:22:22,648
Is it the right time to put an end to a relationship?

478
00:22:23,008 --> 00:22:23,728
Does it have to change?

479
00:22:23,748 --> 00:22:24,749
Does the contract need to change?

480
00:22:24,769 --> 00:22:26,230
Does more people need to be brought on?

481
00:22:26,370 --> 00:22:27,950
All these questions need to happen

482
00:22:28,011 --> 00:22:29,871
when you're changing the scope of your game.

483
00:22:32,428 --> 00:22:33,929
Now, we've given lots of advice for clients,

484
00:22:34,049 --> 00:22:35,750
but we also wanted to touch base on a couple points

485
00:22:36,050 --> 00:22:37,111
in case you're the collaborator.

486
00:22:38,511 --> 00:22:41,513
First, be honest with what is and what isn't your

487
00:22:41,533 --> 00:22:43,694
responsibility, with yourself and with the client.

488
00:22:44,675 --> 00:22:48,417
Be clear about what they are getting

489
00:22:48,497 --> 00:22:49,778
and what you are willing to give.

490
00:22:50,518 --> 00:22:52,519
And that line will always move throughout the contract,

491
00:22:52,559 --> 00:22:54,300
so it's a conversation that needs to happen often.

492
00:22:55,361 --> 00:22:57,682
Get everything laid out first before you start on any work.

493
00:22:57,722 --> 00:22:59,023
We talked about deliverables before.

494
00:22:59,283 --> 00:23:00,464
This applies to contractors too.

495
00:23:01,456 --> 00:23:04,738
And advocate for yourself as best as you can, especially when challenges arise.

496
00:23:05,238 --> 00:23:07,539
This can lead to conflict, but conflict is not bad.

497
00:23:09,040 --> 00:23:12,922
All of the guidelines we've mentioned can and should be brought up when challenges are

498
00:23:12,942 --> 00:23:13,282
happening.

